<hgroup>

<h1><span>HTML</span><span>Components</span></h1>

{{subtitle}}
</hgroup>

Rather than by elements, this resource organizes HTML by components — and with style.

Neither will you learn to conjure elements to create components. Conjuring is wild: one element may create many components, and many elements may create one component. 

Nor will you walk in the wilderness of the untamed. HTML is very tolerant, and this is a ticking time bomb.

You'll browse through an index of components HTML can create. 

You'll walk with style. 


<nav id=overview>
<hgroup>
<h2>Overview</h2>
</hgroup>


HTML uses elements to create components in a tree-like structure.

The root element is <code>html.</code> It contains a <code>head</code> element and a <code>body</code> element.

The <code>head</code> element contains metadata components; optionally, via <code>noscript</code> elements.

The <code>body</code> element contains window components; Windows contain Mixes; Mixes contain Blocks; Blocks contain Media, and Forms, optionally, via Phrases.

[Metadata,](#metadata) [Windows,](#windows) [Mixes,](#mixes) [Blocks,](#blocks) [Phrases,](#phrases) [Media,](#media) and [Forms](#forms) are content models of HTML.

See also: [boilerplate,](#boilerplate) and [rundown](#rundown)
</nav>


<section id=metadata>
<hgroup>
<h2>Metadata</h2>
</hgroup>

Metadata provide information about the document to agents.

HTML has 33 metadata:

<div class="col-list">

- Base URL

- Style Area

- Title

- Icon

- Application Manifest

- Next Document

- Pingback Handler

- Search Document

- Style Link

- Style Alternative

- Document Alternative

- Feed Alternative

- General Link

- Charset Name

- Security Policy

- Style Default

- Redirect Policy

- Application Name

- Author Name

- Description

- Generator Name

- Keywords

- Referrer Policy

- Color Theme

- Color Scheme

- Viewport

- Robot Policy

- General Data

- Script Block

- Script Map

- Script Module

- Script Data

- Language

Per document, there must be no more than one of the following metadata:

- Base URL

- Charset Name

- Security Policy

- Style Default

- Redirect Policy

- Application Name

- Description

- Color Scheme

- Viewport

- Script Map
</div>



There must be some metadate for certain purposes:

- Language Metadata for, example, <q>synthesis tools to determine what pronunciations to use.</q>

- Title Metadata for identification of documents in agents.

There should be some metadata for certain purposes:

- Viewport Metadata for responsive web design

- Base Design System for a readable document by default

- Charset Metadata for appropriate display of characters

</section>


<section id=windows>
<hgroup>
<h2>Windows</h2>
</hgroup>

Windows reveal content to users.

HTML has 2 Windows:

<div class="col-list">

- Primary Window

- Modal Window
</div>

There must be one Primary Window; there can be zero or more Modal Windows.

</section>

<section id=mixes>
<hgroup>
<h2>Mixes</h2>
</hgroup>

Mixes are a set of Blocks and Mixes.

HTML has 33 Mixes:

<div class="col-list">

- Banner Landmark

- Info Landmark

- Header Part

- Footer Part

- Navigation Landmark

- Tangent Landmark

- Navigation Section

- Tangent Section

- General Section

- General Region

- Form Region

- Search Region

- Form Card

- Search Card

- Main Landmark

- Article Section

- Figure Card

- Table Layer

- Description Layer

- Menu List Layer

- Ordered List Layer

- Unordered List Layer

- Address Card

- Details Card

- Fieldset Card

- General Card

- Quote Card

- Anchor Card

- Deletion Card

- Insertion Card

- Map Card

- Noscript Card

- Template Card
</div>

All but one Main Landmark must have a `hidden` attribute. Each of the other landmarks must have an ARIA label when used more than once.

Landmarks should be siblings as they partitions the window — not one another.

Sections, Parts, Description Layer, and Details Card are private mixes as certain blocks or mixes imply them.

Only a sub-section that is independent (Article or General Section) should imply parts or dependent sections. If the root section were to imply, it'll invalidate its semantics as the root.

A Fieldset Card should only be available within a Form Card, Search Card, Form Region, or Search Region as it creates a thematic grouping of their content.

Each Layer eventually contain cards:

- List Layers contain Item Cards. 

- Description Layer contains Description Items. Description Items contain one or more Description Titles, and one or more Description Cards. 

- Table Layers contain optional Table-caption cards, zero or more Table-column Reference, optional Table Head, zero or more Table Body, and optional Table Foot. Table-column Reference contains Table-column Items if there's no <code>span</code> attribute. Table Head, Table Body, and Table Foot contains Table Rows. Table Rows contain Table Titles if in Table Head, otherwise contain Table Data Cards.

</section>



<section id=blocks>
<hgroup>
<h2>Blocks</h2>
</hgroup>

Blocks build Frames with Medias, Forms, Breaks, and Phrases.

HTML has 14 Block components:

<div class="col-list">

- L1 Heading

- L2 Heading

- L3 Heading

- L4 Heading

- L5 Heading

- L6 Heading

- Details Title

- Fieldset Title

- Column Title

- Description Title

- Preformatted Paragraph

- Plain Paragraph

- Kicker Heading

- Subheading
</div>

By the open-close principle, a primary heading (L* Heading) should have a `hgroup` parent element in readiness for any secondary headings.

Heading Blocks should have explicit Sections. Explicit sections, unlike implied sections, can cover content that precedes the heading group or those that follows a sub section. ![](/en/media/need-for-sections.png)

Since there must be a title for a document, there should be a L1 Heading for the document. The former targets agents, the later targets users.

There should only be one L1 Heading per document. Multiple invalidate the semantics as a root heading — there can't be 2 roots.

Root heading should be in the Main Landmark — the primary landmark. Also, it should use a Primary Section; specifically, a General Section as the root section can't be independent of the document.

Main content should be within the root section. Sections make document; anything outside of the root section in the Main Landmark is literarily outside of the document.

There should be no heading block in a secondary landmark. Heading Blocks create Sections and there should not be sections outside of the root section. 

A sub heading should have its section as a child of its parent section; you can't section a non-sectioning element. Also, it must be next in line to avoid missing section.

Like Description Titles, and Column Titles; Sections and other titles should bound their content with a `div` element for consistency.

There should be no implied paragraphs. Implied Paragraphs allows transparent elements to cross them, making them open to misinterpretations.

</section>


<section id=phrases>
<hgroup>
<h1>Phrases</h1>
</hgroup>

Phrases build Blocks with a set of [Media,](#media) [Forms,](#forms) and [Breaks.](#breaks)

HTML has 35 phrases:

<div class="col-list">

- Abbreviation

- Keyword

- Bidirection

- Citation

- Code

- Data

- Definition

- Emphasis

- Idiom

- Input

- Label

- Mark

- Meter

- Progress

- Quote 

- Ruby

- Vague

- Output

- Tangent

- General

- Strong

- Subscript

- Superscript

- Time

- Dormancy

- Variable

- Submit Button

- Reset Button

- Custom Button

- Link 

- Deletion

- Insertion

- Map

- Noscript

- Template

</div>

Button Phrases must contain non-interactive Forms, Media, and Breaks.

A `span` element should wrap text beside a non-breaking content to avoid anonymous content.
</section>



<section id=media>
<hgroup>
<h2>Media</h2>
</hgroup>

Media present information in Blocks. 

HTML has 9 Media:

<div class="col-list">

- Audio Media

- Canvas Image

- Web Document

- Raster Image

- Math Text

- General Media

- Vector Image

- Video Media

- General Text
</div>

Math Text and Vector Images contain elements defined in their namespaces.

Audio and Video Media must contain Sources if no `src` attribute, then zero or more Tracks. Either media must not contain a media.

General Media and Canvas Image may contain content as fallback. But, Canvas Image must not contain these interactive elements: Details Title; Web Document; Audio and Video Media without `controls` attribute; Forms except Buttons, Checkbox Forms, Radio Forms and Select Forms with a <code>multiple</code> attribute or a display size greater than one.

</section>


<section id=forms>
<hgroup>
<h2>Forms</h2>
</hgroup>

Forms accept information in Blocks.

HTML has 21 Forms:

<div class="col-list">

- Selection

- Textarea

- Program

- Textline

- Search

- Telephone

- URL

- Email

- Password

- Date

- Month

- Week

- Time

- Datetime

- Number

- Range

- Color

- Checkbox

- Radio

- File

- Image
</div>

Selection Forms will contain zero or more of Options, Option Groups and Separators. Options contain nothing if there's both label and value attribute; otherwise, text. Option Groups contain zero or more Options.

Textarea Forms contain General Text as the default value.

<aside id=boilerplate>
<hgroup>
<h2>Boilerplate</h2>
</hgroup>
<div>

A web document must have a document type (`doctype`) and a document element (`html`).

It should contain:

- metadata for charset, title, viewport, and a base design system. 

- primary window that contains a Main landmark that contains a root heading.

```html
<!DOCTYPE>

<html lang=en>

  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title> <!-- ... --> </title>
    <meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/@toheeb/base@x.x.x/base.css">
    <script src="https://unpkg.com/@toheeb/base@x.x.x/base-settings.js"></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <div>
      <main>
        <!-- content -->
      </main>
    </div>
    
  </body>
</html>
```
</div>
</aside>

<aside id=rundown>
<hgroup>
<h2>Rethinking HTML</h2>
<p>How HTML uses 116 elements to create 147 components</p>
</hgroup>
<div>

Authors think in components: <q>I need a subheader.</q>

Then, rethink in elements: <q>I need a `p` element that must be after a `h1`, `h2`, `h3`, `h4`, `h5`, or `h6` element that is under a `hgroup` element.</q>

And then, think about content models: <q>is this component allowed as a child? what child components will this allows?</q>

2 problems:

- learning resources are counter intuitive:

  They organise HTML by elements-to-use before content-they-creates. Authors think by content-to-create before elements-to-use. A conflict of expectation.

- [content categories](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#kinds-of-content) are heterogenous and loose for content models:

  __Heterogenous__ because both `p` and `div` elements are Flow content, yet `p` contain Phrasing content while `div` contain Flow content.

  __Loose__ because the spec that strongly encourages an explicit `p` element allows `div` to parent Phrasing content which births an implied `p` element.

Here's how this resource rethinks elements for components, and content categories for content models:

<ul>
<li>

__7__ + 1 elements create multipurpose components: `a`, `del`, `dialog`, `ins`, `map`, `noscript`, `template`, and custom elements.

All except `dialog` and `template` elements are [Transparent content](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#transparent-content-models) that are neither secondary elements nor media components. 

`dialog` element is both a Window, and a Mix.

`a`, `del`, `ins`, `map`, `noscript`, and `template` are both Mixes and Phrases. In addition, `noscript` and `template` modify metadata.
</li>

<li id="metadata-elements">

__6__ elements + 1 attribute create 33 metadata components: `base`, `link`, `meta`, `script`, `style`, and `title`.

`base`, `style`, and `title` elements create one metadata each — total of _3._


A `link` element creates _9_ standard metadata (and _1_ custom link) via some keywords of the `rel` attribute: 

  - `icon`, `manifest`, `next`, `pingback`, `search`, and `stylesheet` creates one metadata each. 

  - `alternate` creates 3 via: an additional `stylesheet` keyword, whether — or not — there's an application mime type attribute.

A `meta` element creates a total of _14_ standard metadata (and _1_ custom meta) via some attributes: 

  - `charset` attribute creates 1. 

  - `http-equiv` creates 3 via its only valid keywords: `content-security-policy`, `default-style`, and `refresh`. 

  - `name` attribute creates 10 via keywords of some standards: `application-name`, `author`, `description`, `generator`, `keywords`, `referrer`, `theme-color`, and `color-scheme` by HTML standard; `viewport` by CSS Standard; and `robots` by SEO standard.

A `script` element creates _4_ metadata via the values of is `type` attribute: "", `importmap`, `module`, and any other Mime Type.

A `lang` attribute on the `html` element creates 1 metadata.

Sum total of _33_: 3 + (9 + 1) + (14 + 1) + 4 + 1

These elements are [Metadata Contents](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#metadata-content) excluding `noscript` and `template` elements.

`noscript` helps convey metadata components for a script-disabled document. `template` helps with reusable markup.


</li>

<li>

__1__ + 1 elements create 2 window components: `body`. 

1 multipurpose element create 1 window component.

Sum total of 1 + 1 elements for 2 components.
</li>

<li>

__20__ + 6 elements create 33 Mixes: 

`header` and `footer` creates Landmarks and Parts — total of 2 elements for 4 components.

`nav` and `aside` creates Landmarks and Sections — total of 2 elements for 4 components.

`section` creates Section and Region — total 1 elements of 2 components

`form`, and `search` creates Regions and Cards — total of 2 elements for 4 components.

`main`, `article`, `figure`, `table`, `dl`, `menu`, `ol`, `ul`, `address`, `details`, `fieldset`, `div`, and `blockquote` elements create a Landmark, Section, Layer, or Card each — total of 13 elements for 13 components.

6 multipurpose elements create 6 components.

Sum total of 20 + 6 elements for 33 components

These elements are [Flow content](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#flow-content) excluding [Block,](#block-elements) [Phrase,](#phrase-elements) [Media,](#media-elements) [Form,](#form-elements) and [Void](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#void-elements) elements; and including [Sectioning content.](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#sectioning-content)
</li>

<li>

__12__ elements create 14 block components

`h1`, `h2`, `h3`, `h4`, `h5`, `h6`, `summary`, `legend`, `th`, `dt`, and `pre` elements create one component each. total of _11_ elements for 11 components.

`p` element creates _3_ components: plain paragraph; kicker and subheader with the help of `hgroup` element. total of 1 element for 3 components.

Sum total of 12 elements for 14 block components.

These elements are [Heading content](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#heading-content) excluding `hgroup` element, and including some from [Flow content.](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#flow-content)
</li>

<li>

__27__ + 6 elements create 35 phrases: 

`abbr`, `b`, `bdi`, `cite`, `code`, `data`, `dfn`, `em`, `i`, `kbd`, `label`, `mark`, `meter`, `progress`, `q`, `ruby`, `s`, `samp`, `small`, `span`, `strong`, `sub`, `sup`, `time`, `u`, and `var` creates 1 component each — total of 26.

`button` element creates 3 based on its `type` attribute.

multipurpose elements create 6.

Sum total of 35: 26 + 3 + 6.

These elements are [Phrasing Content](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#phrasing-content) excluding [Metadata,](#metadata-elements) [Media,](#media-elements) [Form,](#form-elements) [void,](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#void-elements) `bdo`, and `output` elements.

`bdo` is like an explicit `bdi`, and `output` is like an immediate `samp`. 
</li>

<li id="media-elements">

__8__ elements + Text create 9 media:

`audio`, `canvas`, `iframe`, `img`, `math`, `object`, `svg`, and `video`

Text completes the ninth media.

These elements are [Embedded Content](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#embedded-content-2) excluding `embed` and `picture` elements. 

`embed` is practically obsolete. It uses a plugin architecture that modern browsers do not support anymore. `picture` helps `img` with alternative sources.
</li>

<li id=form-elements>

__3__ elements create 21 forms:

`select` and `textarea` elements create a metadata each — total of _2._

An `input` element creates 22 forms via keywords of its `type` attribute, but 3 are better represented via `button` element — total of _19._

Sum total of 21: 2 + 19.
</li>

<li>

__32__ elements are helper elements:

<div class="col-list">

  - area

  - br

  - caption

  - col

  - colgroup

  - datalist

  - dd

  - embed

  - figcaption

  - head

  - html

  - hr

  - li

  - optgroup

  - option

  - picture

  - rp

  - rt

  - selectedcontent

  - slot
  
  - source
  
  - tbody
  
  - td
  
  - tfoot
  
  - thead
  
  - tr
  
  - track

  - wbr
</div>

These are: [Void](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#void-elements) elements excluding [Metadata,](#metadata-elements) [Media,](#media-elements) and [Form](#form-element) elements; and including secondary elements.
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</aside>

</section>
</section>

</section>
</main>
